content:
Before you set up Einstein classification apps, review the data requirements, address data problems early, and learn how to introduce these features to your support team.

To predict values on case fields accurately, Einstein needs lots of closed cases to learn from. You must meet the following minimum data requirements:

* At least 400 closed cases
* Closed cases that have a created date from the past six months
* Cases with a subject or description

Einstein supports encrypted text fields for training only.

Einstein Case Wrap-Up works only with LiveChat, so turn on Chat if it's not active already. While you can start using Einstein Case Wrap-Up without chat transcripts on your past cases, Einstein's recommendations are more accurate when your cases have them.

These issues can hurt the quality of the case data that Einstein analyzes and slows your setup process:

* Few case subjects and descriptions
	+ Improve your case submission process to encourage customers and agents to include clear and consistent information.
* Duplicate cases
	+ Exclude duplicate cases from training data.
* Incorrectly completed fields
	+ Label high-quality cases, and use them as your example case set.
* Overlapping field values
	+ Identify the field's potentially problematic values, and then exclude cases with those values from your model.
* Too many field values
	+ Label high-quality cases, and use them as your example case set.

With Einstein Classification Apps, you can build a model to classify cases in many languages. Take Einstein classification apps for a test run by turning it on in your production org and giving a small group of agents access to the feature.
title: Setting Up Service Cloud with Einstein
